<div class="content_well top">
	<div class="the_hub_content_wrapper the_hub_article">
		<div class="the_hub_content">
		<a href="/category/the-hub/" class="header_link">
		<div class="the_hub_title_wrapper">
			<div class="the_hub_logo">
				<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/plugins/lb-content-widgets/img/lit-horn.svg">
			</div>
			<div class="the_hub_title">
				<h1>The Hub</h1>
			</div>
			<div class="the_hub_slogan">
				<h1>News, Notes, Talk</h1>
			</div>
		</div>
		</a>
		
				<div class="the_hub_item">
			<div class="banner_img">
				<a href="https://lithub.com/what-to-read-next-if-you-loved-sinners/" title="What to read next if you loved <em>Sinners.</em>">
		    		<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/04152025_Movie-Sinners_114145-1240x549.png" alt="" class="post_ft entry_post"/>
		    	</a>
			</div>
			
			<div class="post_content">
				<h1 data-report-url="/what-to-read-next-if-you-loved-sinners/"><a href="https://lithub.com/what-to-read-next-if-you-loved-sinners/">What to read next if you loved <em>Sinners.</em></a></h1>
				
				<div class="author_info">
					<div class="author_photo"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/ESTRed-121-1-scaled-e1711474962955-100x100.jpg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/ESTRed-121-1-scaled-e1711474962955-300x300.jpg 2x" alt="Brittany Allen" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></div>
					<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/brittanyallen/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Brittany&nbsp;Allen</span></a></div>
					<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
					<div class="publish_date">May 14, 2025, 9:36am</div>
				</div>
				
				<p>Much has been said about the <em>vampyr</em>, that evergreen fixation.</p>
<p>The blood-sucking hellspawn is a pliable metaphor, useful for holding the fear of an age. He can symbolize a certain sexual terror, as we most recently witnessed in Robert Eggers&#8217; <a href="https://www.currentaffairs.org/news/who-are-the-real-vampires-in-nosferatu" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Nosferatu</em></a>. Or, as Taika Watiti showed us for several delightful seasons on Hulu&#8217;s <em>What We Do in the Shadows</em>, the vampire can stand in for a general misfitry, a creature who&#8217;s only at home in a house full of fellow weirdos with unruly desires.</p>
<p>Unless you&#8217;ve been living under a rock, you&#8217;ll know that Ryan Coogler, the auteur director behind <em>Black Panther</em>, has entered the chat with a new spin on the myth. In <em>Sinners, </em>the summer blockbuster we deserve, a Depression-era Black community in the rural South is bedeviled by vampires—but it&#8217;s not precisely blood that this coven craves. Coogler dwells on <a href="https://www.aaihs.org/the-sinners-movie-syllabus/" class="external" target="_blank">the vampire&#8217;s colonial missionary aspects</a>. As these bloodsuckers convert, they also steal.</p>
<p>The movie walks a tonal tightrope. Coogler evokes a scrappy, revisionist South that owes something to Zora Neale Hurston, Alice Walker, and Quentin Tarantino. If you&#8217;re like me and dug this gumbo A Lot, here&#8217;s what to read next.</p>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="127478" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-hypocrisy-of-big-business-relationship-to-cannabis/white-negroes-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/white-negroes.jpg" data-orig-size="183,275" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="white negroes" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/white-negroes.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/white-negroes.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-127478 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/white-negroes.jpg" alt="white negroes" width="183" height="275" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/white-negroes.jpg 183w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/white-negroes-40x60.jpg 40w" sizes="(max-width: 183px) 100vw, 183px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Lauren Michele Jackson&#8217;s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780807002735" class="external" target="_blank"><em>White Negroes: When Cornrows Were In Vogue, and Other Thoughts on Cultural Appropriation</em></a></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">The essays in this slim collection take cultural appropriation as the jumping off-point. Through close reads of an archetypal &#8220;Pop Star,&#8221; &#8220;Activist,&#8221; and &#8220;Hipster,&#8221; Jackson examines &#8220;<a href="https://4columns.org/micah-lake/white-negroes" class="external" target="_blank">the desire for black culture by people who are not black</a>.&#8221;</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Writing in <a href="https://4columns.org/micah-lake/white-negroes" class="external" target="_blank"><em>4Columns</em></a>, the critic Lake Micah observed that this book can be read as a response to an antecedent anthology, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780767914970" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Everything But the Burden: What White People are Taking From Black Culture.</em></a> This collection includes musings on cultural appropriation from Hilton Als, Beth Coleman, Robin Kelley, and Arthur Jafa, among other great thinkers.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="177306" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/on-reimagining-the-limitless-potential-of-the-literary-western/the-sisters-brothers-4/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/The-Sisters-Brothers-.jpeg" data-orig-size="199,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="The Sisters Brothers" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/The-Sisters-Brothers-.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/The-Sisters-Brothers-.jpeg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-177306 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/The-Sisters-Brothers-.jpeg" alt="The Sisters Brothers" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/The-Sisters-Brothers-.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/The-Sisters-Brothers--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/The-Sisters-Brothers--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Patrick DeWitt&#8217;s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780062041289" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Sisters Brothers </em></a></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Here we have log line similarity. Two brothers with dubious employment hatch violent schemes, to the end of making a heaven on earth. Though these assassins are white Southerners—and there&#8217;s nary a <em>vampyr</em> in sight—they share with the <em>Sinners</em> twins a complementary co-dependence, an offstage, abusive father figure, and a real respect for gold.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254052" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-to-read-next-if-you-loved-sinners/attachment/9781408177761/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/9781408177761.jpg" data-orig-size="540,829" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="9781408177761" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/9781408177761-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/9781408177761.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-254052 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/9781408177761-195x300.jpg" alt="" width="195" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/9781408177761-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/9781408177761-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/9781408177761-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/9781408177761.jpg 540w" sizes="(max-width: 195px) 100vw, 195px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Katori Hall&#8217;s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781408147023" class="external" target="_blank">Hoodoo Love</a> </em></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">This Memphis-born, much feted playwright is no stranger to Depression-era blues, nor a character that&#8217;s larger than the <a href="https://www.bonappetit.com/story/juke-joints-black-joy?srsltid=AfmBOooE_IwwE6OR8CUWB3M66J4qM9Zpq6VPBqx1bgMy2EyIC6eitcli" class="external" target="_blank">juke joint</a> they came up in. (Hall is the mind behind <a href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9340526/" class="external" target="_blank"><em>P-Valley</em></a> on Starz, which she adapted from her play of roughly the same title.) This &#8220;tale of love, magic, jealousy, and secrets&#8221; follows Toulou, who escapes from the Mississippi cotton fields in the 1930s to pursue her dream of singing the blues in Memphis.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="192720" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-do-we-mean-when-we-call-a-character-a-monster/the-ballad-of-black-tom/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/The-Ballad-of-Black-Tom-.jpg" data-orig-size="250,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The Ballad of Black Tom" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/The-Ballad-of-Black-Tom--188x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/The-Ballad-of-Black-Tom-.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-192720 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/The-Ballad-of-Black-Tom--188x300.jpg" alt="The Ballad of Black Tom" width="188" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/The-Ballad-of-Black-Tom--188x300.jpg 188w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/The-Ballad-of-Black-Tom--38x60.jpg 38w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/The-Ballad-of-Black-Tom--31x50.jpg 31w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/The-Ballad-of-Black-Tom-.jpg 250w" sizes="(max-width: 188px) 100vw, 188px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Victor LaValle&#8217;s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780765387868" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Ballad of Black Tom</em></a></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">LaValle is one of our strongest literary horror writers. The way he braids genres and subverts and honors magical tropes is consistently surprising. This disquieting Jazz Age tale follows a hustling musician who awakens a beast when he &#8220;delivers an occult tome to a reclusive sorceress in the heart of Queens.&#8221; Expect Black magic.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243721" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/ring-shout/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout.jpg" data-orig-size="926,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="ring shout" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-185x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-632x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-243721 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-185x300.jpg" alt="" width="185" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-185x300.jpg 185w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-632x1024.jpg 632w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-768x1244.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-37x60.jpg 37w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-31x50.jpg 31w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout.jpg 926w" sizes="(max-width: 185px) 100vw, 185px" /></p>
<p class="flex text-sm text-purple lg:text-base" style="text-align: center;"><strong>P. Djèlí Clark&#8217;s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250767028" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Ring Shout </em></a></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">This dark historical fantasy novella has been described as sitting squarely on a continuum between Ralph Ellison&#8217;s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679732761" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Invisible Man</em></a> and <em>Buffy the Vampire Slayer</em>. So, safe to say that <em>Sinners</em> is in the neighborhood. A <a href="https://www.npr.org/2020/10/21/924604118/history-and-hatred-drive-the-horror-in-ring-shout" class="external" target="_blank">true Southern Gothic</a> replete with body horror, this story follows Maryse, a young monster-hunter, on a quest to decimate a Ku Klax Klan with supernaturally demonic powers.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="209378" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/19-paperbacks-to-be-grateful-for-this-november/fledgling/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/fledgling.jpeg" data-orig-size="328,500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="fledgling" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/fledgling-197x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/fledgling.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-209378 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/fledgling-197x300.jpeg" alt="fledgling" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/fledgling-197x300.jpeg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/fledgling-39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/fledgling-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/fledgling.jpeg 328w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Octavia Butler&#8217;s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781538724583" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Fledgling</em></a></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">No neo-vampire reading list would be complete without a nod to the late Butler, who took on bloodsuckers in her last published book. Characteristically inventive, this novel follows Shori, a vampire with amnesia who sets out to reconstruct her dark past. A lot of Butler&#8217;s books would make nice <em>Sinners</em> companion reading. Here as elsewhere, themes include the burden of being othered.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="53488" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/12-chilling-books-to-read-for-halloween/annodraculaavonlarge/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/annodraculaavonlarge.jpg" data-orig-size="286,475" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Anno Dracula by Kim Newman" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/annodraculaavonlarge-181x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/annodraculaavonlarge.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-53488 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/annodraculaavonlarge-181x300.jpg" alt="Anno Dracula by Kim Newman" width="181" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/annodraculaavonlarge-181x300.jpg 181w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/annodraculaavonlarge.jpg 286w" sizes="(max-width: 181px) 100vw, 181px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Kim Newman&#8217;s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781781167502" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Anno Dracula</em></a></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Set in an alternate history where Count Dracula married Queen Victoria and ruled the empire, creating a class of vampiric elite, this pastiche-heavy, dazzlingly playful novel picks up where Bram Stoker left off. It&#8217;s the first in a series that makes a &#8220;<a href="https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/kim-newmans-dazzling-genre-multiverse/" class="external" target="_blank">lavish collage of vampire lore</a>.&#8221;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254053" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-to-read-next-if-you-loved-sinners/51fm6gzpunl-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/51fM6gzPUnL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="51fM6gzPUnL._AC_UF1000,1000_QL80_" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/51fM6gzPUnL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/51fM6gzPUnL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-254053 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/51fM6gzPUnL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/51fM6gzPUnL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/51fM6gzPUnL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/51fM6gzPUnL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/51fM6gzPUnL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 662w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Jack Hamilton&#8217;s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780674416598" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Just Around Midnight: Rock and Roll and the Racial Imagination</em></a></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Another heady one for the theorists, or any viewer who&#8217;d like a longer explanation of Preacherboy&#8217;s fever dream sequence on the dance floor. This book, which makes a nice companion read to <a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/a-history-of-rock-music-in-500-songs/id1437402802" class="external" target="_blank">this podcast</a>, offers a useful chronology for any viewer looking to locate the crossroads of Appalachian folk music and Delta Blues.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Through this lineage, Hamilton traces how certain Black musical forms and artists were swallowed by a whiter rock n&#8217; roll. And you&#8217;ll note the vampire-friendly timestamp in the title.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="187454" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2022/81ofi4evuel/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL.jpg" data-orig-size="1600,2400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Claire Kohda, Woman, Eating" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL-683x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-187454 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL-200x300.jpg" alt="Claire Kohda, Woman, Eating" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL-1024x1536.jpg 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL-1365x2048.jpg 1365w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/81Ofi4evUeL.jpg 1600w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Claire Kohda&#8217;s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063140899" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Woman, Eating</em></a></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">This contemporary vampire novel <em>also</em> finds echos of colonialism in Dracula&#8217;s fangs. Lydia is a &#8220;frustrated foodie&#8221; who yearns to eat the Japanese cuisine of her father&#8217;s homeland. But she can&#8217;t stomach anything but blood, due to being undead.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">This literary fiction is concerned with thwarted desires, and finely depicts a person straddling several identities while feeling at home in none. Like Coogler, Kohda also does a lot of mixing around the usual lore.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="144629" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/rural-stories-that-get-it-right-a-reading-list/attachment/9780156505154/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/9780156505154.jpg" data-orig-size="267,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="let the dead bury their dead" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/9780156505154-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/9780156505154.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-144629 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/9780156505154-200x300.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/9780156505154-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/9780156505154-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/9780156505154.jpg 267w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Randall Kenan&#8217;s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780156505154" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Let the Dead Bury Their Dead</em></a></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">The late Randall Kenan wrote about a magical, slippery South. This jewel box of short stories, set in a fictionalized Carolina town, includes hauntings, mediums, talking animals, and—you guessed it—a mad preacher who incites a zombie uprising. Like Coogler, Kenan is interested in the dark side of Southern folkways, and inventive modes of Black survival.</p>
